Name: Barton Creek
description: This is THE place for water-loving doggos! There's even a paddle board rental nearby if you want to join your pupper in the river. Unfortunately, parking can get super crowded around here, especially during the hot months when everyone's dying to take a dip in the cool spring water and the pool next door.

Name: Red Bud Isle
description: Situated on an island, Red Bud Isle is certainly unique. Lining the path on one side is a forested area, and on the other side, pups jump into the Colorado River in several places. Parking is extremely limited at this park, but that means the park is never too crowded. Etiquette rule: wait in line for a parking space to open up.
Fence: no, but it's surrounded by water

Name: Norwood Estate Dog Park
description: Norwood Estate Park is easily accessible from I-35. The park doesn't feature much, but it gets the job done. Includes a fenced in area for the pups and a couple picnic tables.

Name: Onion Creek Metropolitan Park
description: Don't expect anything too fancy from Onion Creek Park. The park is 555-acres of undeveloped woods. Recommended only for the most adventurous of doggos and owners. Expect ponds and rough trails, and bring plenty of water. Undeveloped means no parking, which means your best bet is the dirt shoulder on Nuckols Crossing Road. Like I said, nothing too fancy.

Name: West Austin Dog Park
description: A small, fenced in park with terraced landscape and plenty of chairs. There's a strong community feel here, but make sure you bring bug spray!

Name: Zilker Metropolitan Park
description: As the most popular park in Austin, it's easily understandable why Zilker is great for doggos to roam around! It's vast. It's safe. And it's constantly full of activities. Because it's partly enclosed from the main streets with trees and other shrubbery, pet owners can rest assure that their doggos won't wander too far away. Plus, it's full of parking!

Name: Mueller Lake Park
description: In the middle of the Mueller Development lies this scenic park. It's mostly made up of one trail that circles the lake in the center, with benches and shaded areas dotted along it. There's plenty of food options within walking distance: restaurants to the east and food trucks on the west near the hangar. There's usually a ton of ducks in and around the lake, so be ready if your doggo is a chaser. Parking-wise, there's a dedicated lot on Simond Ave, east of the playground, plus street parking along Simond and Mueller Blvd.

Name: Far West Dog Park/Great Northern Detention Basin
description: Nice open area, short walking trail, swimming area after rainfall

Name: Triangle Commons Park
description: Triangle Commons Park is easily accessible by bus and near the University of Texas, Central Market, and the intramural fields. The park is a component of the Triangle, which is an apartment complex as well as a shopping center. 2 hour garage parking and limited street parking are available.�

Name: Brentwood Neighborhood Park
description:
Quaint neighborhood park filled with families.�
Features a sand volleyball court, two tennis courts, a playground, a public pool, a baseball diamond and a basketball court.

Name: Bull Creek District Park
description: Bull Creek is arguably one of the most beautiful parks in Austin. Right off of Capitol of Texas highway, drivers enjoy stunning views on the way to the park. Features clear waters (only safe for dogs), rocks to climb on and a walking path. Plenty of parking.

Name: Shipe Neighborhood Park
description: This park is great for dogs and owners to enjoy! While there is a massive field that's perfect for running, there's also a tennis court and benches on the other side of the park. But in the summer, be careful of mosquitos! There's usually quite a noticeable amount during that time of the year

Name: Ladybird Lake-Lamar Beach Metro Park
description: Ladybird Park isn't the easiest to commute to since the closest parking lot is about 15 minutes away. But in the mean time, enjoy the view of the water and the smell of fresh air as you and your furry friend walk on a wide trail full of runners and other pet owners alike.�

Name: Peace Point at Town Lake Metropolitan Park
description: If you're a doggo living in Riverside, it doesn't get more convenient than Peace Point. This park offers scenic views of the skyline across the water and a trail leading out onto Lady Bird Lake. You're best off walking here though; street parking is limited.

Name: Pease District Park
description: Pease District is gigantic and has playgrounds, picnic tables, sculptures, etc. So, not only does the park cater to families but it also has long fields great for catching ball with your dog!�

Name: Sparky Pocket Park
description: This park often doesn't have many dogs but that makes it perfect for the pets who need more privacy and security. Plus, it has great sculptures and monuments for dog owners to enjoy!

Name: Auditorium Shores Dog Park
description: Located off Riverside, Auditorium Shores offers a wide open off-leash area for your furry friends to roam. Adventurous doggos can also take a dip in the river. Parking can be a little tricky here. There's a small lot west of the railway bridge that fills up quickly, and 2-hour street parking south of the park.

Name: Metropolitan Park at Walnut Creek�
description: Walnut Creek is primarily a walking/running/biking trail. It boasts of a 3.2 mile stretch of green space that leads to another dog-friendly park, Balcones. Plenty of parking, ideal for� those who want to get active with their dogs.

Name: Mary Moore Searight Metro Park
description: The 1.2 mile off-leash trail here loops around the north section of the park. It has plenty of trash cans to pick up after your pupper. The trail entrance is off of South 1st, but you can also bring your doggo into the main park (on a leash) if you're in the mood for disc golf or more hiking.

Name: Mills Pond
description: Mills Pond is a beautiful, shaded trail that surrounds a lake. Nestled into a neighborhood, this trail exudes a quiet, relaxed vibe. There is a parking lot, but it's kind of hard to find. The entrance is off of Wells Port Dr, between Waterway Bend and Rick Whinery Dr. Otherwise, you can park in the cul-de-sac at the end of Emmet Pkwy

Name: Balcones District Park
description: Balcones is a friendly neighborhood park in North Austin. It features a volleyball court, neighborhood pool and playground. It's also connected to a 3.2 miles (5 kilometers) long trail that leads to Walnut Creek Metropolitan Park. This park is quiet and has a lot of available parking.

Name: Harris Ridge Dog Park
description: Harris Ridge is the perfect park for the pupper who's trying to perfect the tricks he knows. The park features hoops, ramps and teeter totters for Fido to strut his stuff, and it has separate areas for large and small dogs. And for the kids, there's a playground right outside the dog park.�

Name: Cedar Bark Park�
description: Cedar Bark Park is a large, fenced-in dog park right in the heart of Cedar Park. The park is off-leash and separated for large and small dogs. People and pups come from all over the metroplex to enjoy Cedar Bark�s community atmosphere, puppy playground equipment and dog-friendly lake. Other features of the park include: a community pool, picnic areas, plenty of parking, a walking trail, basketball and tennis courts and exercise equipment.

Name: Brushy Creek Lake Park
description: Brushy Creek is less a dog park and more a dog-friendly recreational trail. Enjoy stunning views from the water's edge while you explore the trail with your furry friends. Park features a playground, volleyball court and clean public restrooms.

Name: Yard Bar
description:
A bar combined with a dog park. Doesn't get much better than that.
$5 entry per dog, free if you only want to hang out with other people's dogs.�
The park features trained professionals to keep the area safe so you can sit back, relax, and crack open a cold one with the boys.

Name: Shoal Creek Greenbelt
description: This park isn't the biggest but it's connected to many trails that are dog-friendly. Come to the park (with accessible parking) and embark on your woodsy adventure with your best friend!

Name: Adams-Hemphill Neighborhood Park
description: As the closest northern park near the University of Texas, Adams-Hemphill is really accessible for the many college students who live near the area. While the park looks small on the map, don't be fooled! It has plenty of space for your furry friends to play fetch, catch frisbies or other activities alike. Plus, the park is surrounded by trees, so your dogs can get the security they need.�

Name: Roy G. Guerrero Colorado River Metro Park
description: Roy G Guerrero has many locations near the river where dogs are able to swim but don't forget the towels! These spots are full of sand and mud but also a lot of happiness!
